Trump and the Economy
New York – Financial markets finally woke up to the fact that Trump is indeed the president of the United States.
The world has endured the unfiltered tweets and public statements of the most powerful man in the world for two years, but the obvious question is, what kept it going for so long?
On one hand, investors have been willing to give him the benefit of the doubt until now.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other pro-business and shareholder-friendly policies, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
#1 <s>Many believe that "the grown-ups in the room" would rein in Trump and ensure that government policy stays on track.
#2 <s>This assumption was to some extent borne out during Trump's first year in office, a period when the stock market performed strongly due to expected growth in economic output and corporate profits – thanks to impending tax cuts and deregulation.
#3 <s>In 2017, U.S. stock indices rose by more than 20%.
#4 <s>But this changed dramatically in 2018, especially in the last few months.
#5 <s>Even though corporate profits rose by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated for much of the year and has now fallen sharply.
Currently, all indices are in correction mode (down 10% from recent highs), with tech stock indices such as the Nasdaq having entered a bear market (down 20% or more).
Despite the increased volatility in financial markets reflecting concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turmoil is largely due to Trump.
Early this year, Trump’s reckless tax cuts pushed up long-term interest rates, taking an economy already near full employment to a peak.
In February, worries about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve’s target of 2% triggered the first risk-off episode of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other major US trading partners.
Market concerns about government protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year but are now reaching new heights.
The recent actions by the U.S. towards China seem aimed at sparking a full-blown trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies could bring about stagflation effects (weaker growth and increased inflation).
After all, Trump was preparing to limit foreign direct investment inflows and implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will drag on labor supply growth as the workforce ages and skills misalignment becomes more severe.
Moreover, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan to stimulate private-sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other platforms, Trump constantly criticized business hiring, production, investment, and pricing practices, especially those of tech companies, which were already facing broad opposition and increasing competition from Chinese rivals.
Newly emerging markets were also hit by US policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening pushed up both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the US dollar.
The result was capital flight and rising values of dollar-denominated debt in emerging economies.
Emerging economies that heavily rely on exports suffered losses due to falling commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade ties with China felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy has caused volatility.
The US re-imposition of sanctions on Iran raised oil prices, which subsequently dropped after the US government revoked exemptions and threatened Saudi Arabia to increase oil production.
While US consumers benefit from low oil prices, energy company stocks are struggling.
In addition, excessive price volatility is bad for both producers and consumers as it hinders wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, it now appears that the benefits of last year's tax cuts have almost entirely flowed to the corporate sector rather than higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages for families.
This means that household consumption may slow down soon, further impacting the economy.
However, the recent sharp downturns in both US and global stock markets are mainly due to Trump's own words and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (despite his recent "truce" with Chinese President Xi Jinping), Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve is more damaging. His attacks began in the spring of 2018 when US economic growth was over 4%.
Given these earlier attacks, markets were on edge this month as the Fed correctly decided to raise interest rates while signaling a slower pace of hikes in 2019.
More likely, the Fed’s relatively hawkish stance is a reaction to Trump’s criticisms.
Facing hostile tweets from President Donald Trump on Twitter, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needs to signal that the central bank remains politically independent.
But then, because Congress refused to fund his useless border wall with Mexico, Trump decided to shut down part of the federal government.
This put the markets into near panic mode, and as the government shutdown continued, reports soon emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell – which could turn a correction into a crash.
Just before Christmas, US Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to issue a public statement to calm the markets.
He declared that Trump had no plans to fire Powell, and that the US fiscal situation was strong, which actually highlighted the question of whether the situation really was strong.
And personnel changes within the government that may not affect economic decisions have recently caused market concerns.
The White House chief of staff John Kelly and the Secretary of Defense James Mattis are set to leave, leaving the Trump cabinet without any sound minds.
The rest will all be economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks following Trump's lead.
At present, the possibility of a comprehensive geopolitical conflict with China cannot be ruled out.
A new Cold War could potentially lead to deglobalization, disrupting global supply chains, but it would primarily affect the tech industry, as evidenced by recent cases involving ZTE and Huawei.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the EU and NATO's cohesion when Europe's economy and politics are unstable.
Rosser Mueller's investigation into Trump's 2016 campaign's ties to Russia hangs like a sword of Damocles over his presidency.
Trump is now the financial markets' Dr. Strangelove.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in a cycle of mutually assured economic destruction.
Now, the markets see the danger, and the risks of financial crisis and global recession are rising.
